class Solution {
    public long maximumScoreAfterOperations(int[][] edges, int[] values) {
        List<Integer>[] g = new ArrayList[values.length];
        Arrays.setAll(g, e -> new ArrayList<>());
        g[0].add(-1);
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            int x = e[0], y = e[1];
            g[x].add(y);
            g[y].add(x);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for (int v : values) {
            ans += v;
        }
        return ans + dfs(0, -1, g, values);
    }

    private long dfs(int x, int fa, List<Integer>[] g, int[] values) {
        if (g[x].size() == 1) {
            return values[x];
        }
        long loss = 0;
        for (int y : g[x]) {
            if (y != fa) {
                loss += dfs(y, x, g, values);
            }
        }
        return Math.min(values[x], loss);
    }
}
```
This code is a depth-first search through the tree. The recursive function `dfs` calculates the minimum value that can be added to the score without making the tree unhealthy. This is the minimum loss of values that can be achieved from the node `x`. If `x` has only one child (i.e., `x` is a leaf node), the minimum loss is the value of `x` itself. Otherwise, the minimum loss is the minimum between the value of `x` and the sum of the minimum losses from all its children. The result is the sum of all the values in the tree plus the minimum loss of the root node.

